title: Part 4
content:
Part 4

IT WAS 6:00 PM on the second day. The supplies we acquired included food such as nutritional bars, two kilograms of white rice and canned goods. In addition, there were five new plastic bowls and cups and thoughtfully, five pairs of disposable chopsticks as well. We decided who would eat the white rice with a fair game of rock-paper-scissors, under the condition that no one could refuse without a reason and I became one of the winners. I decided to gratefully accept the warm meal.

White steam billowed gently from the lid of the mess tin over the evening campfire. With the orange-dyed sky at my back, sweat beaded on my hands as I judged the fire's heat. Before long, after the quiet crackling of scorching rice echoed through the quieting forest, I opened the lid and a cloud of fluffy steam billowed out.

Under the setting sun, the freshly cooked white rice shone with a particular brilliance.

Just as I picked up my chopsticks, Shibata, who'd been watching me from a distance, approached with his lips pressed firmly together.

"H-Hey, Ayanokouji. Sorry to bother you before you eat, but you got a sec?"

"I don't mind. What is it?"

"Uh... how should I put it? We're allies now, right? So, I just wanted to say hi, or something..."

He said it while his eyes darted around, scratching his head vigorously.

"Um... this is kind of a weird question, but—uh..."

"Go ahead and say it."

When I prompted Shibata, who was unable to get to the point, his averted gaze met mine.

"The thing I want to ask is...!"

Just as he seemed to have made up his mind and opened his mouth wide, another person approached from behind.

"Pardon me, Shibata, but could you give us a moment? I have something to discuss with Ayanokouji."

It was Kanzaki, who'd taken the lead on serving duty; he approached with an empty mess tin in one hand.

"O-Oh, yeah, n-no problem at all. See ya later, Ayanokouji...!"

As if fleeing, Shibata ran off and left the area.

"Do you need something?"

"I forgot to tell you something important. Regarding the chain of command from here on, Ichinose has said to entrust everything to you, Ayanokouji."

"I see. I appreciate that, but are you ok with that?"

"My satisfaction is irrelevant. Ichinose is the leader of Class D. There are no longer any students in this class who would object to that."

"Such impressive loyalty."

Or perhaps their fangs had already been broken and they simply stopped caring about such trivial matters.

In any case, if things went smoothly, I had no complaints.

Even after I told him what I'd forgotten to mention, Kanzaki made no move to leave.

"Is there something else?"

"...There's something that I just can't seem to accept."

Having said that and pausing for a moment, Kanzaki continued.

"Why did you propose something as unprofitable as an alliance with Class D? I don't understand why you'd go out of your way to lend us a hand and give us a chance to get back on our feet."

"There's no 'why' to it. We were hit with a surprise attack from Ryuuen's class and lost half our classmates in an instant. Without this alliance, we would've inevitably ended up in last place in this special exam. That means the alliance was certainly meaningful."

"That's just looking at the result. You were scheming with Ichinose behind the scenes to form an alliance before the island exam, no, even before we became third-years, weren't you? At the very least, I can't imagine Class C had any need for it at that point. You should be able to recover on your own and compete with Class A and Class B."

Kanzaki had met my father, Ayanokouji Atsuomi. And just as Kanzaki's father admired that man, so did he. Consequently, his opinion of me, Atsuomi's son, was also inevitably high.

"You're overestimating me."

"I'm no fool. It's not just because of your father; I've watched you for more than two years now, so I'm well aware. You have the power to turn the tide of battle all by yourself."

"That's an odd thing to say. I lost half my classmates to Ryuuen's surprise attack. And just this morning, I took an all-or-nothing gamble, lost six people and failed to secure any supplies. If you don't call that overestimating me, what do you call it?"

"Of course, no one is perfect. Anyone can make a miscalculation like that. Or rather, even before that, Class C just isn't suited for fighting."

"That's precisely why. Can't you think of the alliance as insurance, just in case? It won't have a major impact on Class C if Class D rises up a bit. And it's useful in other ways, too. If we couldn't count on Class D growing and rising over this next year, then Horikita and Ryuuen would only have to focus on Class C. It's easier for us to operate if their attention is divided. I'm not extending a hand for nothing."

In terms of overall strength, Class C was certainly a step ahead.

But in reality, it was Class C that was now asking for help and Class D accepted.

"Class D is still developing. You can count on your potential for growth."

"Still developing when we're a lap behind?"

"There's plenty of time. If we can manage a one-two finish in this special exam, the gap with the top classes will be trivial. Am I wrong?"

"I can't shake the feeling that they're still out of our reach... But I suppose Ichinose believes; believes that with you, we can aim for that—even after all these failures, Ichinose doesn't seem to doubt your abilities."

That was probably connected to why she said she was leaving the command to me.

I finished my white rice and gently closed the lid of my mess tin.

Then I stood up and moved to Kanzaki's side.

"It would be a problem if Ichinose were the only one aiming for Class A. You, Kanzaki, need to be on the same page as her and more than anything, you need confidence and resolve."

"Confidence and resolve..."

"If you still don't get it, then you should take a good look at the view from here. You may want to deny it, but the strength that only Class D possesses is on clear, almost amusing, display."

In the scene spread out before him, students from Class C and Class D were conversing without any wariness.

"You should try to better understand just how incredible it is to be trusted."

It was an environment where Class D, superior in numbers, could defeat Class C with a single surprise attack if they so chose.

If their opponents were Class A or Class B? They definitely couldn't have felt at ease. They would've been fraught with anxiety, wondering when they'd be backstabbed.

"Why don't you come visit the sports gym sometime?"

"...That's out of the blue. What brought that on?"

"It's what they call being 'so close, yet so far.' You should start by getting to know what kind of person Ichinose is up close."

I knew I might not get a favorable answer now, but it would be enough to simply plant the thought in his mind.
